HEADWORD: Ruck
<hw>Ruck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A roc.</def> <mark>[Obs.
or prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ruck
<hw>Ruck</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rucked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rucking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Icel <ets>hrukkast</ets> to
wrinkle, <ets>hrukka</ets> wrinkle, fold.]</ety> <def>To draw into
wrinkles or unsightly folds; to crease; <as>as, to <ex>ruck</ex> up a
carpet</as>.</def> <rj><au>Smart.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ruck
<hw>Ruck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>hrukka</ets>. Cf.
<er>Ruck</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>A wrinkle or crease in a
piece of cloth, or in needlework.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ruck
<hw>Ruck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Dan. <ets>ruge</ets> to brood,
to hatch.]</ety> <def>To cower; to huddle together; to squat; to sit, as
a hen on eggs.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Gower.
South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sheep that <qex>rouketh</qex> in the fold.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Ruck
<hw>Ruck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Ruck</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A heap; a rick.</def> <mark>[Prov Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The common sort, whether persons or things; <as>as,
the <ex>ruck</ex> in a horse race</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ruck</qex> in society as a whole.</q> <rj><qau>Lond. Sat.
Rev.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ructation</ent>⟦br⟧
